entry.title: [rust] Conditionalize prebuilt stdlib targets.
entry.content:
In some cases (e.g. Android) we don't distribute prebuilt Rust standard

libraries, so we have no choice but to build the stdlib from scratch.

This was already the case, and Rust targets linked fine on such

platforms. But, in the case of builds which targeted all gn targets, we

would have tried to run the build steps pertaining to the prebuilt Rust

stdlib which didn't exist, and such builds failed.



This CL ensures that all such build steps are behind conditions to

ensure that they are never triggered in cases where such a prebuilt

stdlib doesn't exist.



For ease of review, this CL does not restructure the file at all. The

next CL in the series reshuffles the lines to reduce the excessive

number of conditionals added by this CL.



This should have no functional effect except to disable some broken gn

targets on some builds.

entry.title: [fedcm] Skip the Profile Permission Prompt when scopes are broader
entry.content:
The AuthZ API introduces a "scope" parameter that allow an RP to ask

for more than the user's basic profile (name/email/id and picture),

for example, access to the user's calendar / contacts / social graph.



When that occurs, the browsers uses a pop-up window, rather than a

mediated permission prompt to gather the user's authorization.



In this CL, behind a flag, we introduce part of that algorithm.

Namely, when a scope isn't ["name", "email", "sub" and "picture"]

we skip the mediated permission prompt after the account chooser,

and we hit the id_assertion_endpoint directly after the account

chooser.



The IdP gets to assess if a pop-up window is necessary (based on

the scope parameter), and open one in case it is necessary

(implemented in the last CL).



The algorithm is described in more details in the design doc [1].



[1] https://docs.google.com/document/d/1uSHNIT2wZj0ojmelsOa698oZQ2XC7VLM6WnxYkHU4fk/edit#

entry.title: [color] Fix recursive color recipe for Windows high contrast
entry.content:
This CL addresses an infinite recursion bug on windows high contrast.



Currently if a recusive recipe is defined in the pipeline clients

will experience a stack overflow when attempting to compute the

resulting color.



For e.g. in one mixer

mixer[kColorOmniboxResultsBackgroundHovered] = {

kColorOmniboxResultsBackgroundSelected};

And in another

mixer[kColorOmniboxResultsBackgroundSelected] = {

kColorOmniboxResultsBackgroundHovered};



This was occuring due to such a set of looping definitions in the

windows high contrast mixer and the omnibox mixer.



This should be handled more gracefully by the pipeline however this

CL addresses the problem acutely by eliminating the recusive recipe.

entry.title: Use true damage for has_damage propagation
entry.content:
PrewalkRenderPass() already has to compute an accurate damage for each

render pass, minus the real render pass damage, which is taking into

account via surface damage. The client marks if render pass has damage

entry.title: Introduce SharedDictionaryWriterOnDisk
entry.content:
This CL introduces SharedDictionaryWriterOnDisk class which stores the

binary of dictionary as an entry of SharedDictionaryDiskCache. Its

FinishCallback is called when the entire dictionary binary has been

stored to the disk cache, or when an error occurs. This class handles

zero-sized data as an error.



Currently, SharedDictionaryWriterInMemory's FinishCallback can be called

with zero-sized data. To make the behavior consistent, this CL also

modifies SharedDictionaryWriterInMemory to call FinishCallback with an

error when no data has been written.



Also this CL changes SharedDictionaryDiskCache to support using mocked

Disk Cache backend for testing

entry.title: Revert "[iOS] Extract visibility changes from NTP start/stop"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 8d0480e1672dfd352d7c87e064e590d1935dd986.



Reason for revert: Crashing in crbug.com/1433265



Original change's description:

> [iOS] Extract visibility changes from NTP start/stop

>

> Remove NTP visibility changes from the coordinator's start/stop

> functions. Starting the NTPCoordinator should not necessarily mean

> that the NTP has become visible, ie. when creating an NTP in an

> inactive web state. Therefore, these calls should be separate.

>

> This fixes an issue where NTPDidChangeVisibility:YES would be

> triggered on an already visible NTP when switching from one NTP

> to another.

>

> This is a step in the direction of having more meaningful and

> intentional start/stop calls, as it allows the coordinator lifecycle

> to be controlled without necessarily updating the NTP visibility.

>

> By separating navigation calls between the NTPTabHelper and the TabEventsMediator, we'll be able to distinguish NTP visibility

> changes between web states or within the same web state. This will

> be done in a follow-up CL and will help with things like saved scroll

> position, as it will be clearer when a user navigated back to an NTP expecting to retain their position.

>

> Small refactoring of NTP visibility function, removing unnecessary properties like `sceneInForeground` and `viewPresented`.

>

> This fixes a crash introduced in M113 (crrev.com/c/4290479). Before that

> CL, the problematic code was only hit if EnablePasswordsAccountStorage

> was enabled and the user tried to move a local password to the account.

> Now it's hit regardless of any flags, as long as one follows the

> repro instructions in the title of this CL.

>

> The root cause is settings coordinators receive a non-incognito Browser

> even when they are started from incognito. Looking for a tab in the

> non-incognito browser will fail if only incognito tabs are open.

>

> The adopted fix is to look for tabs also in other browsers, using

> BrowserList. A better fix would be to refactor some of the code

> //components/password_manager/ to avoid unnecessarily depending on

> tabs. But that's a much larger effort and riskier to merge back.
